	^ &nbsp;https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10305423/&nbsp;&nbsp;

The estimation of glomerular filtration rate (GFR) is crucial for assessing kidney function. Measured GFR (mGFR) using exogenous markers, like urinary or plasma clearance of filtration substances, is the gold standard but is not routinely used due to its complexity. Renal function tests typically rely on estimated GFR (eGFR) using serum creatinine or creatinine clearance (Clcr), which, despite limitations, remains the most common method.[1] Emerging markers like cystatin C offer potential for improved accuracy and may become routine in the future. The KDIGO classification of chronic kidney disease (CKD) categorizes CKD into stages based on eGFR values, aiding in diagnosis and treatment planning.[2] While exogenous substances provide precise measurements, endogenous markers are being explored for better clinical integration.



